content.description: This is the arete on the right side of the Cube offers some good movement and is well protected. If anyone knows the actual name of this route or the FA don't hesitate to suggest a change/modify the page.
content.protection: 4 bolts. 2 bolt anchor w/ rap rings.
content.location: First bolt is just left of the two bolt anchor for Obfuscate and Eludicate.

climbs.name: Obfuscate
climbs.fa: Ken Klis, Aaron Stireman, Chris Koppl, Clayton

content.description: Can be a hard start or an easy one, definitely a test in balance up top with slopers, incuts and a pinch at the exit.
content.location:
Left side of the cube, under the main arete.

Really hidden, probably more than any other route, hence the name.

content.description: A little dirty, but overall some good movement on solid rock.
content.location: Located on the shorter side of the cube that faces the East Summit Blocks. Three prominent jug rails are a landmark, and take you up a short pinch and sloper crux.

content.description: A powerful line up the steepest arete of the cube, so far an unsent crux.
content.location: Rap off the obvious bolt station to the downhill side of the cube. The orange rock on the overhanging arete is the route. Starts in a 5.7 hand crack, or loose 10a face on the uphill side of the gully. Move up and right out a roof and over the arete.

climbs.name: Elucidate
climbs.fa: Aaron Stireman, Chris Koppl, Ken Klis

content.description:
It's pretty clear standing under it that its just going to take a strong campus move off of a small crimp (v6/7), or a huge reach to gain an incut, in which case the rig goes a full number easier at about .11b.

We added a belay bolt on the starting slab that's easy to tie into, since the crack underneath was too rotten for gear, and what is cragging without a 5.8 belay stance?
content.location: Under the Cube on the Headwall
